{
  "executive_summary": "Decompose the courier platform monolith into 5 services aligned with domain boundaries: Order, Courier, Location Tracking, Payment, and Notification. Customer Account remains a shared kernel. The decomposition prioritizes deployment independence (the stated goal), isolates the high-throughput location tracking write path, and protects payment consistency — while staying realistic for an 8-person team that should NOT attempt more than 5 services initially.",

  "architecture": {
    "components": [
      {
        "name": "Order Service",
        "responsibility": "Order lifecycle: placement, status transitions, cancellation, order history. Owns the Order aggregate and orchestrates the fulfillment saga (courier assignment, payment capture).",
        "boundaries": "Owns orders table, order_items, order_status_history. Does NOT own courier assignment logic — it requests assignment from Courier Service. Does NOT process payments — it triggers payment via events."
      },
      {
        "name": "Courier Service",
        "responsibility": "Courier onboarding, availability management, assignment algorithm, route optimization. Owns the Courier aggregate including shift schedules and assignment state.",
        "boundaries": "Owns couriers, courier_availability, assignments, routes tables. Consumes location data from Location Tracking Service for routing decisions but does NOT own location storage."
      },
      {
        "name": "Location Tracking Service",
        "responsibility": "Ingest, store, and serve real-time courier GPS coordinates. Handles the 5,000 writes/sec peak load. Provides current-position queries and recent trail queries.",
        "boundaries": "Owns location_updates time-series data. Stateless ingest pipeline. No business logic beyond geofencing. This is the hottest write path and must be independently scalable. Publishes location events for Courier Service consumption."
      },
      {
        "name": "Payment Service",
        "responsibility": "Payment authorization, capture, refunds, payout to couriers. Integrates with payment gateway (Stripe/Adyen). Owns ledger and transaction records with strict ACID consistency.",
        "boundaries": "Owns payments, transactions, refunds, courier_payouts tables. Synchronous API for payment operations — no eventual consistency on money movement. Isolated deployment so PCI compliance scope is minimized."
      },
      {
        "name": "Notification Service",
        "responsibility": "Fan-out of customer and courier notifications across email, SMS, and push channels. Template management. Delivery tracking and retry logic.",
        "boundaries": "Owns notification_templates, notification_log. Purely reactive — consumes domain events from other services. No business decisions. Generic subdomain — could be replaced with a third-party service."
      },
      {
        "name": "Customer Account (Shared Module — NOT a separate service)",
        "responsibility": "Customer profiles, authentication, preferences. Kept as a shared library/module rather than a standalone service to avoid an authentication bottleneck that every request must traverse.",
        "boundaries": "Owns users, customer_profiles tables. Deployed as a shared library consumed by Order and Notification services. Extract to a service ONLY when a second team needs independent ownership."
      }
    ],
    "interfaces": [
      {
        "from": "Order Service",
        "to": "Courier Service",
        "contract": "POST /assignments {order_id, pickup_location, dropoff_location} → {assignment_id, courier_id, estimated_eta}. Synchronous request-reply for assignment. Order Service retries with backoff on failure.",
        "coupling_type": "request-reply (synchronous)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Order Service",
        "to": "Payment Service",
        "contract": "OrderPlaced event → Payment Service authorizes hold. OrderDelivered event → Payment Service captures. OrderCancelled event → Payment Service releases hold. Synchronous fallback API for refund requests: POST /refunds {order_id, amount, reason}.",
        "coupling_type": "event-driven with synchronous fallback for refunds"
      },
      {
        "from": "Location Tracking Service",
        "to": "Courier Service",
        "contract": "LocationUpdated event stream {courier_id, lat, lng, timestamp, accuracy} published to message broker. Courier Service subscribes and updates its internal nearest-courier index. Also exposes GET /couriers/{id}/location for on-demand queries.",
        "coupling_type": "event-driven (async stream)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Order Service",
        "to": "Notification Service",
        "contract": "Domain events: OrderConfirmed, CourierAssigned, OrderDelivered, OrderCancelled → Notification Service maps event type to template and channels, then dispatches. Fully async, fire-and-forget from Order Service perspective.",
        "coupling_type": "event-driven (async, fire-and-forget)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Courier Service",
        "to": "Notification Service",
        "contract": "CourierAssigned, DeliveryCompleted events → Notification Service sends courier-facing notifications.",
        "coupling_type": "event-driven (async)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Payment Service",
        "to": "Order Service",
        "contract": "PaymentAuthorized, PaymentCaptured, PaymentFailed, RefundCompleted events back to Order Service to advance order state machine.",
        "coupling_type": "event-driven (async)"
      }
    ],
    "data_flow": "1) Customer places order → Order Service creates order, publishes OrderPlaced event. 2) Payment Service receives OrderPlaced, authorizes payment hold, publishes PaymentAuthorized. 3) Order Service receives PaymentAuthorized, calls Courier Service synchronously to request assignment. 4) Courier Service queries Location Tracking Service for nearest available courier, assigns, publishes CourierAssigned. 5) Location Tracking Service continuously ingests GPS pings from courier app via lightweight HTTP/gRPC endpoint, publishes LocationUpdated stream. 6) Courier Service consumes location stream to update ETAs. 7) On delivery confirmation, Order Service publishes OrderDelivered → Payment Service captures payment, Notification Service sends receipt. Throughout: Notification Service reacts to all domain events to keep customer informed.",
    "patterns_used": [
      {
        "pattern": "Strangler Fig Migration",
        "rationale": "Do NOT rewrite from scratch. Extract services one at a time from the monolith, starting with Location Tracking (highest isolation benefit, lowest domain coupling) then Payment (compliance isolation). The monolith continues to serve other capabilities during migration."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Saga (Orchestration) for Order Fulfillment",
        "rationale": "Order placement spans multiple services (payment auth, courier assignment). Use an orchestrated saga in Order Service to coordinate the multi-step process with compensating actions on failure. Orchestration over choreography because the team is new to distributed systems — explicit control flow is easier to debug."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "CQRS for Location Tracking",
        "rationale": "Location Tracking has a 50:1 write-to-read ratio at peak. Separate the write path (append-only time-series ingestion) from the read path (current position lookups, trail queries). Write path can use a time-series store (TimescaleDB/InfluxDB); read path can use a Redis cache of latest positions."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Event-Driven Architecture with Central Broker",
        "rationale": "Domain events decouple services temporally and reduce direct service-to-service calls. Use a single message broker (Kafka or RabbitMQ) as the event backbone. Keeps operational complexity manageable for an 8-person team — one broker to operate, not point-to-point connections."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Database-per-Service",
        "rationale": "Each service owns its data store. This is the whole point of the decomposition — without data isolation, you just have a distributed monolith. Location Tracking gets a time-series DB, Payment gets a relational DB with strict ACID, others get Postgres."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "API Gateway",
        "rationale": "Single entry point for mobile/web clients. Handles auth, rate limiting, request routing. Keeps clients from needing to know service topology. Use an off-the-shelf gateway (Kong, AWS API Gateway) — do not build one."
      }
    ]
  },

  "domain_model": {
    "bounded_contexts": [
      {
        "name": "Order Management",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["Order (root: order_id — contains line items, status, delivery address, timestamps)", "OrderSaga (tracks fulfillment state machine: created → payment_authorized → courier_assigned → in_transit → delivered | cancelled)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Courier Operations",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["Courier (root: courier_id — contains profile, vehicle type, availability status, current assignment)", "Assignment (root: assignment_id — links order to courier, tracks pickup/dropoff state)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Location Tracking",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": ["LocationStream (root: courier_id — append-only series of GPS coordinates; not a traditional aggregate — modeled as a time-series stream with latest-position materialized view)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Payments",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["PaymentTransaction (root: transaction_id — contains authorization, captures, refunds as a ledger; immutable append-only entries for auditability)", "CourierPayout (root: payout_id — batch payout to courier for completed deliveries)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Notifications",
        "classification": "generic",
        "aggregates": ["NotificationRequest (root: notification_id — template, channel, recipient, delivery status)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Customer Identity",
        "classification": "generic",
        "aggregates": ["Customer (root: customer_id — profile, auth credentials, preferences, addresses)"]
      }
    ],
    "context_map": [
      {
        "upstream": "Order Management",
        "downstream": "Payments",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier. Order Management defines the events (OrderPlaced, OrderDelivered, OrderCancelled) that Payments must conform to. Payment Service translates these into its own internal ledger model."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Order Management",
        "downstream": "Notifications",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier. Notifications is a conformist — it accepts whatever events Order Management publishes and maps them to templates."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Location Tracking",
        "downstream": "Courier Operations",
        "relationship": "Open Host Service. Location Tracking exposes a published language (LocationUpdated events with standardized schema) that Courier Operations consumes for routing decisions."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Courier Operations",
        "downstream": "Order Management",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier. Courier Operations publishes assignment and delivery events that Order Management consumes to advance order state."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Payments",
        "downstream": "Order Management",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier (bidirectional dependency). Payments publishes PaymentAuthorized/Failed events back to Order Management. This bidirectional coupling is intentional — it's the saga coordination loop."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Customer Identity",
        "downstream": "Order Management",
        "relationship": "Shared Kernel. Customer ID and basic profile are shared via a common library. Minimal surface area — just customer_id, name, contact info."
      }
    ]
  },

  "trade_offs": [
    {
      "decision": "5 services (not 6) — Customer Account stays as shared module",
      "gains": "Avoids the 'auth service as bottleneck' anti-pattern. Reduces operational surface for an 8-person team. One fewer service to deploy, monitor, and on-call for.",
      "sacrifices": "Customer Account changes require redeploying consuming services. Less isolation for the identity domain.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Extract Customer Account as a 6th service — rejected because it would be on the critical path of every request and the team lacks experience operating service meshes or managing cascading auth failures"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Orchestrated saga over choreography for order fulfillment",
      "gains": "Explicit state machine in Order Service makes failure modes visible and debuggable. Easier for a team new to distributed systems to reason about.",
      "sacrifices": "Order Service becomes a coordination point — higher coupling to the saga logic. Choreography would be more loosely coupled.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Pure choreography with event chaining — rejected because debugging distributed choreography requires distributed tracing maturity this team likely doesn't have yet", "Process manager as a separate service — over-engineering for current scale"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Synchronous call for courier assignment (Order → Courier) instead of async",
      "gains": "Customer gets immediate confirmation with courier name and ETA. Simpler UX flow. Assignment is fast (sub-second) if courier index is in-memory.",
      "sacrifices": "Temporal coupling between Order and Courier services. If Courier Service is down, order placement fails.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Async assignment with 'finding your courier' UX — viable but worse customer experience for a courier platform where speed is competitive advantage"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Single message broker (Kafka) instead of point-to-point",
      "gains": "One piece of infrastructure to operate. Event replay capability. Consumer groups for scaling. Natural event sourcing foundation for future.",
      "sacrifices": "Kafka operational complexity. RabbitMQ would be simpler for the current event volume.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["RabbitMQ — simpler operations but no replay/retention. Acceptable alternative if the team has RabbitMQ experience", "AWS SNS/SQS — good if already on AWS, lower ops burden, but vendor lock-in"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "CQRS for Location Tracking with time-series write store + Redis read cache",
      "gains": "Write path handles 5,000/sec without contending with read queries. Redis serves current-position queries in <1ms. Clean separation of hot path.",
      "sacrifices": "Two data stores to operate. Slight staleness on read path (acceptable — location data is inherently stale by the time it's consumed).",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Single Postgres with partitioning — could handle 5K writes/sec but would degrade under concurrent read load and time-range queries", "Pure Redis — fast but no durable history for analytics/disputes"]
    }
  ],

  "flexibility_points": [
    {
      "area": "Notification channels",
      "evolution_path": "Adding new channels (WhatsApp, in-app) requires only changes to Notification Service. No other service needs modification. Template-driven design means new notification types can be added via configuration."
    },
    {
      "area": "Payment provider",
      "evolution_path": "Payment Service encapsulates gateway integration behind an internal interface. Switching from Stripe to Adyen (or adding multi-provider support) is contained within Payment Service."
    },
    {
      "area": "Assignment algorithm",
      "evolution_path": "Courier assignment logic is isolated in Courier Service. Can evolve from simple nearest-courier to ML-based optimization without affecting Order Service — the interface contract stays the same."
    },
    {
      "area": "Location Tracking storage",
      "evolution_path": "Can swap from TimescaleDB to InfluxDB or even a custom solution. The write API and event schema are the stable contracts; storage is an implementation detail behind the service boundary."
    },
    {
      "area": "Customer Account extraction",
      "evolution_path": "Currently a shared module. When a second team forms or auth requirements become complex (SSO, MFA), extract to a service. The shared library interface becomes the service API — minimal change to consumers."
    }
  ],

  "rigidity_points": [
    {
      "area": "Order state machine",
      "reason": "The order fulfillment saga is the core business process. Changes to state transitions ripple across Payment and Courier services. This is intentionally rigid — order lifecycle semantics should change slowly and deliberately."
    },
    {
      "area": "Domain event schemas",
      "reason": "Events are the contracts between services. Schema changes require coordinated consumer updates. Use schema versioning (e.g., CloudEvents with schema registry) from day one. Breaking changes require a new event version, not mutation of existing schema."
    },
    {
      "area": "Payment ledger model",
      "reason": "Financial records are append-only and immutable. The ledger structure should be designed carefully upfront because retroactive changes to financial data structures are extremely costly (audit, compliance, reconciliation)."
    }
  ],

  "risks": [
    {
      "risk": "Distributed monolith: services extracted but still tightly coupled via synchronous calls and shared database",
      "severity": "critical",
      "mitigation": "Enforce database-per-service from the start — no shared database connections. Lint CI pipeline to reject cross-service direct DB queries. Limit synchronous calls to the one justified case (courier assignment). Everything else goes through events."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Operational overwhelm: 8 engineers suddenly operating 5 services + message broker + API gateway + multiple databases",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Strangler Fig migration — extract ONE service at a time. Start with Location Tracking (most isolated, clearest boundary). Run it in production for 4-6 weeks before extracting the next. Invest in observability (distributed tracing, centralized logging) BEFORE extracting the first service, not after."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Saga failure handling: incomplete orders where payment is authorized but courier assignment fails, leaving money held",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Implement compensating transactions in the saga: if assignment fails after 3 retries, release payment authorization and notify customer. Add a saga timeout (e.g., 30 seconds) that triggers automatic compensation. Monitor for stuck sagas with alerts."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Location data loss during high-throughput bursts (5K writes/sec peak)",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Buffer writes through Kafka topic before persisting to time-series DB. Kafka handles burst absorption. Courier app should have local queue that retries on failed sends. Accept that some location points may be lost — the business tolerates gaps (next update comes in 10 seconds)."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Event ordering and idempotency issues causing inconsistent state across services",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Partition Kafka topics by order_id and courier_id to guarantee ordering within an entity. Make all event consumers idempotent using event_id deduplication. Include monotonic sequence numbers in events for out-of-order detection."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Team splits poorly — one engineer owns a critical service alone (bus factor = 1)",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "With 8 engineers and 5 services, assign pairs (not individuals) to services. Two pairs own the two core services (Order, Courier). One pair owns Payment. Location Tracking and Notification are simpler — one pair covers both initially. Rotate quarterly."
    }
  ],

  "implementation_guidance": {
    "recommended_approach": "Strangler Fig in 4 phases over ~6 months. Phase 1 (weeks 1-4): Set up infrastructure — API gateway, message broker, centralized logging, distributed tracing. Deploy alongside monolith. Phase 2 (weeks 5-10): Extract Location Tracking Service. It has the clearest boundary, no inbound dependencies, and the strongest scaling motivation. Route GPS ingestion to new service while monolith still serves reads. Phase 3 (weeks 11-16): Extract Payment Service. Motivated by PCI compliance isolation and deployment independence. Requires implementing the order-payment event contract. Phase 4 (weeks 17-24): Extract Order Service and Courier Service together (they have the tightest coupling). Notification Service can be extracted at any point — it's the simplest extraction.",
    "files_to_create_or_modify": [
      "services/location-tracking/ — New service: lightweight HTTP/gRPC ingest API, Kafka producer, TimescaleDB writer, Redis cache updater",
      "services/payment/ — New service: payment gateway integration, ledger, event consumer/producer",
      "services/order/ — Extracted from monolith: order API, saga orchestrator, event producer",
      "services/courier/ — Extracted from monolith: assignment API, location consumer, routing engine",
      "services/notification/ — New service: event consumer, template engine, channel dispatchers",
      "infrastructure/docker-compose.yml — Local development environment with all services, Kafka, databases",
      "infrastructure/api-gateway/ — Gateway configuration (Kong/similar) with routing rules",
      "shared/events/ — Event schema definitions (protobuf or JSON Schema) shared across services via artifact, NOT code sharing",
      "shared/customer-identity/ — Shared library for customer auth/profile (until extracted to service)"
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "Each service follows hexagonal architecture internally: domain core with no infrastructure dependencies, ports defining interfaces, adapters implementing ports for specific technologies. This makes it easy to swap infrastructure (e.g., changing Location Tracking's DB) without touching domain logic. Use contract testing (Pact) between services rather than end-to-end integration tests — E2E tests across 5 services will be slow and flaky.",
    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "DO NOT extract all services simultaneously — Strangler Fig one at a time, validate in production, then proceed",
      "DO NOT share databases between services — this is the #1 way teams end up with a distributed monolith",
      "DO NOT build a custom API gateway — use an off-the-shelf solution (Kong, Envoy, cloud-native)",
      "DO NOT skip observability setup — you need distributed tracing BEFORE the first extraction, not after you're debugging production incidents blind",
      "DO NOT use synchronous calls between services except where absolutely necessary (courier assignment is the one justified case)",
      "DO NOT create a shared ORM or shared domain models across services — each service owns its own models. Shared event schemas are the ONLY shared artifact",
      "DO NOT attempt event sourcing across the board — use it only for Payment ledger where auditability justifies the complexity. Other services use standard state-based persistence"
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 82,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "Service boundaries align with domain boundaries and team structure — these are natural seams",
      "Location Tracking isolation is clearly the right first extraction — highest write throughput, lowest domain coupling",
      "Payment isolation is well-justified by consistency requirements and PCI compliance scope reduction",
      "Event-driven decoupling between services is the standard approach for this problem shape"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Kafka vs RabbitMQ vs cloud-native (SNS/SQS) choice depends on team's existing experience and infrastructure — I chose Kafka as default but RabbitMQ may be more appropriate if operational simplicity is paramount",
      "Exact team pairing assignments depend on individual engineer strengths not visible from this description",
      "Whether the 6-month timeline is realistic depends on test coverage of the existing monolith and how tangled the current codebase is"
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "The monolith has a reasonably well-structured codebase where domain boundaries are at least partially reflected in code organization (modules/packages)",
      "The team has basic containerization experience (Docker) — if not, add 4-6 weeks for infrastructure learning",
      "The 5,000 writes/sec for location tracking is the actual measured peak, not a theoretical estimate",
      "Payment processing uses an external gateway (Stripe/Adyen) rather than custom payment infrastructure",
      "The team is willing to invest in observability tooling (Jaeger/Zipkin, ELK/Datadog) as a prerequisite to decomposition"
    ]
  }
}

